VIt's no surprise that were you to peel back the glossy veneer from Hollywood you'd uncover a seething pit of ego-powered corruption, turbo-charged vanity and industrial strength greed.Director David Cronenberg and script writer Bruce Wagner don't so much strip-mine Tinseltown of its rampant avarice and preening narcissism than emotionally frack the place to reveal nary a scintilla of humility or decency.Nobody comes out of this looking good - from Julianne Moore's faded star Havana Segrand bitchily fighting against a youth-obsessed system that's discarded her to homophobic, anti-semitic child celebrity Benjie (Bird) viciously ensuring no-one threatens his top billing.In pimped-up mansions under the blazing Californian sun, this obscenely pampered community never relaxes next to its azure pools but are biliously obsessed with faux status and the accretion of meaningless amounts of wealth.Into their twisted world arrives wide-eyed Agatha (Wasikowska), whose scarred face and arms mark her apart from the flawless bodies of LA's jeunesse dorée but - with the help of limo driver/actor/writer Jerome (Pattinson) - manages to land the job of PA to the terminally insecure Havana.Havana's determined to land the role her (more famous) mother played in a hot new movie but - despite the ministration of Carrie Fisher playing herself - looks set to lose out to a younger model, a state of affairs amplified by hallucinations of her dead mom taunting her.Seeking inner (and outer) peace, she turns to grasping self-help guru Sanford Weiss (Cusack), an oily, Bentley-driving chancer whose own 13-year-old son - the vile Benjie - is terrified that he's being upstaged by a new arrival on his long-running TV movie series Bad Babysitter.In a barely watchable scene, the child star visits a children's hospital where a young cancer patient has to correct his impression she's dying of Aids.
