V \u000aIn 1968, when Stanley Kubrick\u2019s 2001: A Space Odyssey was released, on 70 mm and in a 2.21:1 aspect ratio, it would be another year before Apollo 11 landed on the moon.
p3510
tp3511
a(I0
VThat spectacle was small-screen\u2014broadcast live, in grainy black-and-white to TVs back on Earth, Neil Armstrong took "one giant leap for mankind," ending the Space Race.
p3512
tp3513
a(I0
VBut by 1979, the $500-million-plus grossed planet-wide for George Lucas\u2019 $11-million space opera signalled the launch of Hollywood\u2019s Blockbuster Race.
p3514
tp3515
a(I0
VEver since, we\u2019ve had soaring, FX-engineered spectacles on NASA-level budgets taking us far, far away.
p3516
tp3517
a(I0
VThese unearthly epics, charting a meteoric course to the top of the box office, are fitted with marketing rocket-boosters, piloted by A-list stars, and boast more of a stratospheric emotional arc than any space agency\u2019s plotted in decades.
p3518
tp3519
a(I0
VFor a super-sized-movie\u2019s director, it\u2019s all about mission control.
p3520
tp3521
a(I0
VChristopher Nolan, who in 1998 made his feature debut with black-and-white neo-noir Following (budget: $6000), has become a go-to populist auteur for blockbusters.
p3522
tp3523
a(I0
VHe\u2019s earned such a banked-on reputation for delivering huge films under budget that, in an unprecedented deal, Warner Bros traded rights to two franchises and a property to-be-determined to Paramount (the project\u2019s initiator and owners of the script, by Nolan\u2019s brother Jonathan) to secure international distribution for Interstellar (budget: $165 million).
p3524
tp3525
a(I0
