p6017
tp6018
aa(lp6019
(I0
VHollywood has always been more than happy to take on the role of America's hand-wringing moral conscience, churning out movies that lift the lid on Uncle Sam's more unsavoury deeds both at home and abroad.
p6020
tp6021
a(I0
VDodgy goings-on in Iraq (Green Zone, Battle For Haditha), dirty tricks in Latin America (Salvador, Missing), the ignominious tragedy of Vietnam (Born on the Fourth of July, Casualties of War), institutionalised homophobia (Milk, Philadelphia), CIA duplicity (The Bourne saga, Clear and Present Danger)...
p6022
tp6023
a(I0
VThe list goes on and on...with one notable exception.
p6024
tp6025
a(I0
VSlavery.
p6026
tp6027
a(I0
VA subject so thorny Tinseltown has largely steered clear of despite it being one of the most indelible stains on the Stars'n'Stripes.
p6028
tp6029
a(I0
VAs Brit director Steve McQueen points out "Slavery lasted 400 years and there are less than 20 [films].
p6030
tp6031
a(I0
VWe have to redress that balance and look at that time in history."
p6032
tp6033
a(I1
VWith searing conviction he achieves this in a relentless, raw and visceral condemnation of a viciously racist regime that condemned its victims to a life of hard labour with random cruelties thrown in and justified by a skewed interpretation of the Old Testament.
p6034
tp6035
a(I0
VThe shocking system of serfdom is seen through the eyes of Solomon Northrup (Ejiofor), a comfortably-off violinist who lives a conventional 19th century life with his wife and children in the accepting town of Saratoga Springs in upstate New York.
p6036
tp6037
a(I0
VHowever, this all changes when he accepts an invitation from two white businessman to perform at a musical engagement in Washington DC.
p6038
tp6039
a(I0
VPlied with drink, he groggily wakes up to find himself literally in chains and en route to a life of servitude in Louisiana.
p6040
